{{Infobox scientist | name = Jill Adler | image = | image_size = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1951|01|31}} | nationality = [[South Africa]] | fields = [[Mathematics education]] | workplaces = [[University of the Witwatersrand]] | alma_mater = B Sc, M Ed, PhD [[University of the Witwatersrand]] | awards = | website = [https://www.wits.ac.za/staff/academic-a-z-listing/a/jilladlerwitsacza/ Jill Adler] }}
'''Jillian Beryl Adler''' née '''Smidt''' (born 31 January 1951 in [[Johannesburg]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mathunion.org/o/Organization/GA/GA-Santiago/candidatesCV/ICMI/ICMIAdler.pdf|title=Curriculum Vitae, Professor Jill Adler|publisher=Mathunion.org|accessdate=18 October 2017 |language=}}</ref> is a [[South Africa]]n Professor of [[Mathematics education]] at the [[University of the Witwatersrand]] and the President of the [[International Commission on Mathematical Instruction]] (2017 - 2020). Adler's work has focused on the teaching and learning of mathematics particularly in [[Multilingualism|multilingual]] classrooms.
==Career and impact== Jill Adler was born in [[Johannesburg]],<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mathunion.org/icmi/activities/awards/the-hans-freudenthal-medal-for-2015/|title=International Mathematical Union (IMU): The Hans Freudenthal Medal for 2015|website=www.mathunion.org|language=en|access-date=2017-10-18}}</ref> [[South Africa]]. She obtained her undergraduate and postgraduate degrees from the [[University of the Witwatersrand]].<ref name=":0" /> Currently, she serves as the Chair of Mathematics Education at [[University of the Witwatersrand|Wits University]] and as the President of the [[International Commission on Mathematical Instruction]] (2017 - 2020).<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=http://africabusinesscommunities.com/news/international-maths-body-appoints-south-african-professor-jill-adler-president.html|title=International Maths Body appoints South African Professor, Jill Adler, President|last=Communities|first=Africa Business|work=Africa Business Communities|access-date=2017-10-18|language=nl-NL}}</ref> Adler's work has focused on the teaching and learning of mathematics particularly in [[Multilingualism|multilingual]] classrooms<ref name=":1" /> as well as the [[professional development]] of [[secondary school]] maths teachers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wits.ac.za/education/research/jill-adler---sarchi-chair-in-mathematics-education/|title=Jill Adler - SARChI Chair in Mathematics Education - Wits University|last=Johannesburg|first=The University of the Witwatersrand,|website=www.wits.ac.za|language=en|access-date=2017-10-18}}</ref> She has an A-rating, the highest possible, from the [[National Research Foundation of South Africa]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wits.ac.za/research/distinguished-researchers/|title=Distinguished Researchers - Wits University|last=Johannesburg|first=The University of the Witwatersrand,|website=www.wits.ac.za|language=en|access-date=2017-10-18}}</ref> From 2009 to 2014 Professor Adler was a [[Visiting scholar|visiting professor]] at [[King's College London]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kclpure.kcl.ac.uk/portal/en/persons/jill-adler(f593ba9c-dfe9-4174-a39d-30968d8751be).html|title=Professor Jill Adler|last=King's College London|first=|date=2015|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=18 October 2017}}</ref> She is a member of the [[Academy of Science of South Africa]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.assaf.org.za/index.php/about-assaf/members|title=Members|last=User|first=Super|website=www.assaf.org.za|language=en-gb|access-date=2017-10-18}}</ref>
==Awards and honors== * [[International Commission on Mathematical Instruction|ICMI]] [[Hans Freudenthal]] Medal (2015) <ref name=":0" />
